"1290","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England"},"en":{"1240–1314":"1240–1314","1242–Female":"1242–Deceased","1230–Female":"1230–Deceased","1215–Male":"1215–Deceased","1220–Female":"1220–Deceased","1314":"1314","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1220":"1220","1242":"1242","1230":"1230","1240":"1240","1290":"1290","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cave","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place in East Yorkshire called Cave, apparently from a river name derived from Old English <i>cāf</i> ‘swift’.","English (of Norman origin): nickname from Norman and Picard Old French <i>cauf</i> (from Latin <i>calvus</i>) ‘bald’.","French: topographic name for someone who lived in or near a cave, from Old French <i>cave</i> ‘cave’, ‘cellar’ (from Latin <i>cavea</i>, a derivative of <i>cavus</i> ‘hollow’)."],"variants":[{"name":"Cavin","meanings":["Scottish (Wigtownshire): variant of <b>Caveen</b>, a shortened form of Manx <i>Mac Dhaimhín</i>, son of <i>Daimhín</i>. The personal name is a diminutive of Gaelic <i>damh</i> ‘bard, poet’.","French: diminutive of   Cave  ."]},{"name":"Caves","meanings":["English: variant of   Cave  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Keeve","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Cave  . This surname is rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Chaffee","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): descriptive nickname from a derivative of Old French <i>chauf</i> ‘bald’ (from Latin <i>calvus</i>). Compare   Cave  ."]},{"name":"Cavett","meanings":["Scottish (of French origin): altered form of French <b>Cavet</b>, which is either a diminutive of   Cave   3 or a metonymic occupational name for a laborer, one who used a <i>cavet</i>, an Old Occitan word for a tool for clearing ground for cultivation."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":19,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":50,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Alexander Cave was born in 1240, in Northamptonshire, England, his father, Peter Cave, was 25 and his mother, Joan or Elena Bromflete, was 20. He had at least 1 daughter with Matilda Malodaen. He died in 1314, at the age of 74."},"et":{"1240–1314":"1240–1314","1242–Female":"1242–Surnud","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","1215–Male":"1215–Surnud","1220–Female":"1220–Surnud","1314":"1314","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1220":"1220","1242":"1242","1230":"1230","1240":"1240","1290":"1290","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"1240–1314":"1240–1314","1242–Female":"1242–Kuollut","1230–Female":"1230–Kuollut","1215–Male":"1215–Kuollut","1220–Female":"1220–Kuollut","1314":"1314","1259